- Excuse me.


230
00:19:19.371 --> 00:19:21.414
Underneath it all, very simple.

231
00:19:21.623 --> 00:19:23.291
Isn't he wonderful?

232
00:19:28.213 --> 00:19:30.965
Listen. Order me
a corned-beef sandwich, will you?


233
00:19:31.174 --> 00:19:34.802
Lean, now, no fat, no gristle.
And a cream soda and a pickle.


234
00:19:35.804 --> 00:19:38.639
- Mr. Cordova wants a...
- Stay right here. It's all right.


235
00:19:38.849 --> 00:19:41.142
That maniac. Honestly! Say, Hal?

236
00:19:41.351 --> 00:19:43.394
- Yes, Miss Marton.
- The maestro wants his, uh...


237
00:19:43.603 --> 00:19:46.188
I know. The corned beef.
It's in his dressing room already.


238
00:19:46.398 --> 00:19:47.440
Hal, this is Mr. Hunter.

239
00:19:47.649 --> 00:19:50.067
- This is Hal Benton, Jeff's manager.
- Nice to meet you.


240
00:19:50.277 --> 00:19:51.944
- I'm a great admirer of yours.
- Thank you.


241
00:19:52.154 --> 00:19:55.406
- When did you get in town?
- I got off the train a couple of hours ago.


242
00:19:55.615 --> 00:19:58.576
- Wasn't that curtain slower tonight?
- It was my fault. I'm sorry.


243
00:19:58.785 --> 00:20:02.455
No, don't change it. Keep it that way.
It's wonderful. Doubles the applause.


244
00:20:02.664 --> 00:20:04.498
- This is Tony Hunter.
- How do you do?


245
00:20:04.708 --> 00:20:08.294
Sorry, kids. Be with you soon as I get out
of this sackcloth and ashes...


246
00:20:08.503 --> 00:20:12.131
Max, what happened to that amber spot?
It was way off.


247
00:20:12.341 --> 00:20:13.674
Must have more light on me there.

248
00:20:13.884 --> 00:20:15.968
Don't let us keep it a secret
I'm in the show.


249
00:20:16.178 --> 00:20:17.386
- Excuse me.
- Hello, sweetheart.


250
00:20:17.596 --> 00:20:19.221
- You look wonderful.
- Thank you.


251
00:20:19.431 --> 00:20:23.225
Hal, call a full dialogue rehearsal, will you?
Friday, for the full company.


252
00:20:23.435 --> 00:20:26.520
Sloppy diction. The original was in Greek,
but this is in English.


253
00:20:26.730 --> 00:20:30.900
Don't let us keep it a secret it's in English.
I want to catch the matinee tomorrow...


254
00:20:31.109 --> 00:20:33.736
...of Man in a Mousetrap.
- Can't do. We got a drama lecture...


255
00:20:33.945 --> 00:20:35.529
Never mind. We'll work it out somehow.

256
00:20:35.739 --> 00:20:37.740
Jeff, this is Tony Hunter.

257
00:20:37.949 --> 00:20:39.825
Yeah, I know. We just met.

258
00:20:41.745 --> 00:20:42.787
Mr. Hunter.

259
00:20:42.996 --> 00:20:44.830
- I beg your pardon.
- I'm glad to know you.


260
00:20:45.040 --> 00:20:46.207
So happy to meet you.

261
00:20:46.416 --> 00:20:49.168
You have no idea
how delighted I am to see you.


262
00:20:49.378 --> 00:20:51.128
- Delighted and thrilled.
- Thank you.


263
00:20:52.798 --> 00:20:55.091
We need our theater greats right here.

264
00:20:55.300 --> 00:20:58.719
So when Lily and Lester said they were
doing a show with Tony Hunter...


265
00:20:58.929 --> 00:21:00.763
...that's all I had to know.

266
00:21:00.972 --> 00:21:04.642
I'm dropping every other project,
and there are plenty, believe me.


267
00:21:05.477 --> 00:21:09.897
That's wonderful, Mr. Cordova,
but all this... The classics...


268
00:21:10.524 --> 00:21:14.527
- Do you really want to do a musical?
- Musical, musical!


269
00:21:14.736 --> 00:21:18.614
I'm sick of these artificial barriers
between the musical and the drama.


270
00:21:18.949 --> 00:21:22.535
In my mind, there is no difference
between the magic rhythms...


271
00:21:22.744 --> 00:21:26.414
...of Bill Shakespeare's immortal verse
and the magic rhythms...


272
00:21:26.623 --> 00:21:28.999
...of Bill Robinson's immortal feet.

273
00:21:29.668 --> 00:21:32.211
Hal, write that down.
I'll use it at Princeton.


274
00:21:32.421 --> 00:21:34.213
It's already down. 
You used it last week.

275
00:21:34.423 --> 00:21:36.966
I tell you, if it moves you,
if it stimulates you...


276
00:21:37.175 --> 00:21:39.260
...if it entertains you, it's theater.

277
00:21:39.469 --> 00:21:42.638
When the right combination gets together
and it spells theater...


278
00:21:42.848 --> 00:21:46.016
...I got to be right
in there up to my armpits.

279
00:21:46.685 --> 00:21:48.060
That's higher than usual.

280
00:21:48.270 --> 00:21:50.604
Now, that's what I wanted
Tony to hear you say.


281
00:21:50.814 --> 00:21:55.151
I tried to tell him how you feel, but I knew
that you could say it so beautifully.


282
00:21:55.360 --> 00:21:57.695
Lily, you splendid animal.

283
00:21:57.904 --> 00:22:00.739
Take your hands off my wife
and let's get down to business.


284
00:22:00.949 --> 00:22:03.951
Now I have here a script.
It's great. It's ready to roll.


285
00:22:04.161 --> 00:22:07.621
Jeff, I want you to take this home.
I want you to read it tonight...


286
00:22:07.831 --> 00:22:10.875
But before I do,
give me a rough idea of the plot.


287
00:22:11.084 --> 00:22:13.627
- Now?
- Throw it at me for a quick impression.


288
00:22:13.837 --> 00:22:15.713
- I'm dying to hear it.
- You tell it.


289
00:22:15.922 --> 00:22:18.048
- You do it so much better.
- Lester, honestly.


290
00:22:18.258 --> 00:22:20.718
- Please, Lily, tell them.
- Lester, honestly.


291
00:22:21.553 --> 00:22:25.556
With Tony in mind, we naturally
visualize a light and intimate show.


292
00:22:25.765 --> 00:22:29.643
We want to give him a chance to play
a charming guy, with just enough plot...


293
00:22:29.853 --> 00:22:32.730
...to make him do lots
of gay and varied numbers.


294
00:22:33.148 --> 00:22:36.484
He's a writer and illustrator
of children's books...


295
00:22:36.693 --> 00:22:38.152
...but to get in the real dough...

296
00:22:38.361 --> 00:22:41.322
...on the side,
he writes lurid murder mysteries...


297
00:22:41.531 --> 00:22:43.824
...full of violence and buckets of blood.

298
00:22:44.576 --> 00:22:47.244
The success of these
makes him feel he's sort of...


299
00:22:47.454 --> 00:22:50.039
...sold his soul to the devil,
but he keeps on doing it.


300
00:22:50.248 --> 00:22:53.459
There's lots of comedy implications
with his friends, played by us.


301
00:22:53.668 --> 00:22:56.295
- With his girl.
- I love this. Terrific possibilities.


302
00:22:56.505 --> 00:22:58.631
And some of the best numbers
we've ever written!


303
00:22:58.840 --> 00:23:02.968
Children's playground, a reform school,

304
00:23:03.178 --> 00:23:06.388
- And a number about a murder mystery!
- You two are the end.


305
00:23:06.640 --> 00:23:10.226
- Tony, I'm so glad!
- Some of the best lines we've written.


306
00:23:11.603 --> 00:23:13.604
What do you think, Jeff?

307
00:23:21.696 --> 00:23:23.572
Kids, you're geniuses.

308
00:23:23.782 --> 00:23:26.575
The whole thing
is a brilliantly imaginative idea.


309
00:23:26.785 --> 00:23:28.077
Why, Jeff!

310
00:23:28.286 --> 00:23:31.789
You've hit on something
that's not only great as a musical...


311
00:23:31.998 --> 00:23:34.708
...but valid in terms
of today, of modern life.

312
00:23:34.918 --> 00:23:36.627
Jeff, I'm so glad!

313
00:23:36.836 --> 00:23:40.381
Of course, these modern thrillers,
he's got to keep turning them out.


314
00:23:40.590 --> 00:23:42.466
They make him fame, money. He's caught.

315
00:23:42.676 --> 00:23:44.176
It's a funny situation.

316
00:23:44.386 --> 00:23:48.013
Of course! It's brilliant,
contemporary, perceptive.


317
00:23:48.265 --> 00:23:51.392
This story's a modern version of Faust.

318
00:23:52.978 --> 00:23:55.187
- Faust?
- You're kidding, Jeff.


319
00:23:56.273 --> 00:23:59.733
I guess I didn't tell it right.
I didn't bring out the point.


320
00:23:59.943 --> 00:24:04.113
But you did bring out the point admirably.
You used the phrase:


321
00:24:04.322 --> 00:24:06.657
"He sells his soul to the devil."

322
00:24:07.033 --> 00:24:10.202
Now, that's the line you have to follow
straight through.


323
00:24:10.453 --> 00:24:13.038
Just like Faust,
this man is tempted by the devil...


324
00:24:13.248 --> 00:24:17.626
...and his compromise, his sellout,
must end in eternal damnation.


325
00:24:18.295 --> 00:24:20.129
That'll leave them laughing.

326
00:24:20.338 --> 00:24:24.258
Kids, you've got a choice here
between a nice little musical comedy...


327
00:24:24.467 --> 00:24:27.177
...and a modern musical morality play...

328
00:24:27.387 --> 00:24:29.722
...with meaning and stature!

329
00:24:30.432 --> 00:24:34.101
- But we don't want to write Faust.
- You're taking me too literally.


330
00:24:34.311 --> 00:24:36.645
I want to do
your story. I love it!

331
00:24:36.980 --> 00:24:39.565
But I want to angle it
to bring out the analogy...


332
00:24:39.774 --> 00:24:42.443
...between the Faust legend
and this man's story.


333
00:24:43.028 --> 00:24:46.655
Won't this make it heavy?
Is this a box-office idea?


334
00:24:46.865 --> 00:24:48.157
Is Faust box-office?

335
00:24:48.366 --> 00:24:51.493
Listen, Faust by Christopher Marlowe,
Faust by Goethe, Faust by Gounod...


336
00:24:51.703 --> 00:24:52.953
...Faust by Hector Berlioz.

337
00:24:53.163 --> 00:24:57.041
I tell you, anyone who's touched this
legend has turned it into a gold mine.


338
00:24:57.250 --> 00:24:58.834
It's got to be a smash.

339
00:24:59.919 --> 00:25:02.671
It could still have all the fun in it,
couldn't it?


340
00:25:02.881 --> 00:25:06.717
- Yeah, and some stature thrown in.
- Now, kids, I'm happy about this.


341
00:25:07.010 --> 00:25:09.470
- Really happy.
- So are we, Jeff.


342
00:25:09.679 --> 00:25:11.013
This publisher you mentioned...

343
00:25:11.222 --> 00:25:14.058
...obviously, he could be
the counterpart of the devil.


344
00:25:18.855 --> 00:25:20.898
Evil personified!

345
00:25:21.524 --> 00:25:25.653
Leading all mankind
into the paths of temptation!


346
00:25:26.404 --> 00:25:29.823
- But nobody could play it like you.
- Nobody's going to.


347
00:25:30.033 --> 00:25:32.076
You mean you're going to play it?

348
00:25:32.410 --> 00:25:35.245
The part of the girl... 
Somebody fresh.

349
00:25:35.455 --> 00:25:39.166
Somebody with fire, charm, grace, beauty.
Gabrielle Gerard.


350
00:25:39.376 --> 00:25:42.670
- Gerard? She's a ballet dancer.
- She doesn't want to do a show.


351
00:25:42.879 --> 00:25:45.255
- She turns them all down.
- Nobody ever turns me down.


352
00:25:45.465 --> 00:25:48.175
Do you really think you could get her?
What a cast!


353
00:25:48.385 --> 00:25:52.888
Tony Hunter, Jeff Cordova,
Gabrielle Gerard! Tony! Isn't this exciting?


354
00:25:53.098 --> 00:25:54.264
Yeah.

355
00:25:54.683 --> 00:25:58.435
Now, look, this is going to be
a sort of modern Faust story.


356
00:25:59.104 --> 00:26:03.357
I play the Faust character. You play
the Devil. It'll have stature, importance.


357
00:26:03.775 --> 00:26:06.610
- I have to dance with this ballet dancer?
- She's wonderful.


358
00:26:06.820 --> 00:26:07.903
It'll be great.

359
00:26:08.113 --> 00:26:11.365
It'll be great for somebody.
I'll pick up my marbles and go home.


360
00:26:11.574 --> 00:26:14.368
Fellas, bless you and good luck,
but this just ain't for me.


361
00:26:14.577 --> 00:26:16.453
I know what I can do,
and I'm sticking to it.


362
00:26:16.663 --> 00:26:19.665
That's the trouble. You've stuck to it,
and you're stuck with it.


363
00:26:19.874 --> 00:26:22.292
- What?
- Nobody admires you more than I.


364
00:26:22.502 --> 00:26:25.504
I've seen every show
and every movie you've ever done...


365
00:26:25.714 --> 00:26:27.297
...but let's face some brutal facts.

366
00:26:27.507 --> 00:26:30.509
Times have changed, Tony.
You haven't changed with them.


367
00:26:30.719 --> 00:26:34.722
- You've gone stale.
- Then you certainly don't need me.


368
00:26:35.682 --> 00:26:37.057
Yes, we do!

369
00:26:37.267 --> 00:26:39.560
Because you can be greater
than you ever were!


370
00:26:39.769 --> 00:26:43.272
We are going to make you explode
on the theater scene like a skyrocket!


371
00:26:43.481 --> 00:26:46.400
Not just the old trademark,
with the top hat, tie, and tails...


372
00:26:46.609 --> 00:26:48.569
...but a great artist
at the peak of his powers.


373
00:26:48.778 --> 00:26:52.406
The new Tony Hunter. 
Tony Hunter, 1953!

374
00:26:52.615 --> 00:26:55.617
- But can I do it?
- It's a challenge to all of us...


375
00:26:55.827 --> 00:26:58.287
...but that's what the theater's about:
a challenge.


376
00:26:58.496 --> 00:27:00.748
Whatever I am,
whether it's a new me or an old me...


377
00:27:00.915 --> 00:27:02.624
...remember, I'm still just an entertainer.

378
00:27:02.834 --> 00:27:05.210
What do you think I am?
What do you think they are?


379
00:27:05.420 --> 00:27:07.963
What do you think the theater is?
It's all entertainment!


380
00:27:08.173 --> 00:27:11.175
Believe me, there is no difference
between the magic rhythms...


381
00:27:11.384 --> 00:27:13.969
...of Bill Robinson's immortal feet...
- You said that before.


382
00:27:14.179 --> 00:27:17.765
All right, what did Bill Robinson do?
He danced on the stairs, didn't he?


383
00:27:17.974 --> 00:27:20.517
Now I happen to play Oedipus the king
on the same stairs.


384
00:27:20.727 --> 00:27:23.187
What's the difference? 
We're all theater.

385
00:27:24.272 --> 00:27:25.814
Show me the greatest tragic actor...

386
00:27:26.024 --> 00:27:28.108
...or the lowest red-nosed comic
in burlesque...


387
00:27:28.318 --> 00:27:30.736
...and I'll show you an entertainer. We're all...

388
00:27:32.697 --> 00:27:34.698
Jeff, are you all right?

389
00:27:35.366 --> 00:27:37.826
Everything that happens in life

390
00:27:38.036 --> 00:27:40.412
Can happen in a show

391
00:27:40.997 --> 00:27:44.208
You can make 'em laugh
You can make 'em cry


392
00:27:44.626 --> 00:27:48.670
Anything, anything can go

393
00:27:51.382 --> 00:27:54.510
The clown with his pants falling down

394
00:27:54.719 --> 00:27:58.096
Or the dance that's a dream of romance

395
00:27:58.306 --> 00:28:02.309
Or the scene where the villain is mean

396
00:28:03.061 --> 00:28:05.646
That's entertainment

397
00:28:06.105 --> 00:28:09.149
The lights on the lady in tights

398
00:28:09.359 --> 00:28:12.986
Or the bride with
the guy on the side

399
00:28:13.196 --> 00:28:17.324
Or the ball where
she gives him her all

400
00:28:17.784 --> 00:28:20.369
That's entertainment!

401
00:28:20.954 --> 00:28:24.164
The plot can be hot
Simply teeming with sex


402
00:28:24.666 --> 00:28:27.668
A gay divorcée who is after her ex

403
00:28:28.962 --> 00:28:31.338
It could be Oedipus Rex

404
00:28:31.548 --> 00:28:35.467
Where a chap kills his father
And causes a lot of bother


405
00:28:35.677 --> 00:28:38.679
The clerk who is thrown out of work

406
00:28:38.888 --> 00:28:42.307
By the boss who
was thrown for a loss

407
00:28:42.517 --> 00:28:46.019
By the skirt who is doing him dirt

408
00:28:46.354 --> 00:28:48.355
The world is a stage

409
00:28:48.565 --> 00:28:52.317
The stage is a world of entertainment

410
00:29:05.456 --> 00:29:07.708
That's entertainment!

411
00:29:14.924 --> 00:29:16.592
All right!

412
00:29:19.804 --> 00:29:22.139
That's entertainment!

413
00:29:29.981 --> 00:29:31.773
Look what I can do.

414
00:29:40.867 --> 00:29:42.409
It's still me!

415
00:29:57.258 --> 00:30:00.344
The doubt while the jury is out

416
00:30:00.553 --> 00:30:03.931
Or the thrill when they're reading the will

417
00:30:04.140 --> 00:30:07.726
Or the chase for
the man with the face

418
00:30:08.853 --> 00:30:11.188
That's entertainment!

419
00:30:11.898 --> 00:30:14.816
The dame who is known as the flame

420
00:30:15.026 --> 00:30:18.487
Of the king of an underworld ring

421
00:30:18.696 --> 00:30:22.532
He's an ape who won't let her escape

422
00:30:23.534 --> 00:30:25.827
That's entertainment!

423
00:30:26.621 --> 00:30:29.706
It might be a fight
Like you see on the screen


424
00:30:30.333 --> 00:30:33.794
A swain getting slain
For the love of a queen


425
00:30:34.671 --> 00:30:39.299
Some great Shakespearean scene
Where a ghost and a prince meet


426
00:30:39.509 --> 00:30:41.134
And everyone ends in mincemeat

427
00:30:41.344 --> 00:30:44.346
The gag may be waving that flag

428
00:30:44.555 --> 00:30:48.016
That began with a Mr. Cohan

429
00:30:48.226 --> 00:30:51.979
Hip hooray, the American way

430
00:30:52.188 --> 00:30:53.939
The world is a stage

431
00:30:54.524 --> 00:30:59.695
The stage is a world of entertainment

432
00:31:03.199 --> 00:31:06.284
- You gone yet, Hal?
- I'm in here, Jeff, on the phone.


433
00:31:06.494 --> 00:31:08.996
Drama desk? Hello, Mike. It's Hal.

434
00:31:09.205 --> 00:31:12.624
You know that item Mr. Cordova sent you
about signing Gabrielle Gerard...


435
00:31:12.834 --> 00:31:13.875
...for the Marton show?

436
00:31:14.085 --> 00:31:17.546
There's been a mistake.
I wonder if there's still time to kill it.


437
00:31:17.755 --> 00:31:20.549
- Yeah. I'd appreciate it. Thanks, kid.
- Why did you do that?


438
00:31:20.758 --> 00:31:23.218
To save you from making an idiot
of yourself in print.


439
00:31:23.428 --> 00:31:25.721
- You know you can't get Gerard.
- Why?


440
00:31:25.930 --> 00:31:29.307
Because Paul Byrd won't let her
do a show. He's a tough customer.


441
00:31:29.517 --> 00:31:32.019
He's not only her choreographer,
he's also her boyfriend.


442
00:31:32.186 --> 00:31:33.603
She doesn't make a move without him.

443
00:31:35.023 --> 00:31:36.064
That will be Paul Byrd now.

444
00:31:36.274 --> 00:31:39.609
- It's 3 in the morning.
- Let him in, Hal, will you?


445
00:31:44.323 --> 00:31:45.741
- Hello, Paul.
- Where are they?


446
00:31:45.950 --> 00:31:47.409
He's in there.

447
00:31:47.785 --> 00:31:48.869
Hello, Paul.

448
00:31:49.078 --> 00:31:50.328
- Where is he?
- Who?


449
00:31:50.538 --> 00:31:52.998
- Oscar Hammerstein.
- Home in bed, I hope, at this hour.


450
00:31:53.207 --> 00:31:55.709
- Who is it? Dick Rodgers?
- What are you talking about?


451
00:31:55.918 --> 00:31:58.378
Didn't you say the greatest producer
of musicals today...


452
00:31:58.546 --> 00:31:59.880
...was here and wanted to see me?

453
00:32:00.089 --> 00:32:03.925
- That's me. I'm doing a musical.
- Did you get me out of bed...


454
00:32:07.722 --> 00:32:09.181
I see what this is all about.

455
00:32:09.390 --> 00:32:13.143
You needn't go any further because
the answer is no on Gabrielle Gerard.


456
00:32:13.352 --> 00:32:15.645
Gabrielle... Paul, 
I don't follow you.

457
00:32:15.855 --> 00:32:18.940
Gabrielle is not going to do a show.
She's too important to ballet.


458
00:32:19.150 --> 00:32:20.817
This has nothing to do with Gabrielle.

459
00:32:21.360 --> 00:32:25.530
Paul, I want you to do the choreography
for the greatest musical in years.


460
00:32:25.907 --> 00:32:27.824
Oh. Oh.

461
00:32:28.034 --> 00:32:30.077
- I'm sorry...
- That's why I wakened you, Paul.


462
00:32:30.286 --> 00:32:34.039
I'm so keyed up I just can't sleep.
You know how brilliant the Martons are.


463
00:32:34.248 --> 00:32:35.874
This time, they've excelled themselves.

464
00:32:36.084 --> 00:32:38.877
This show is a choreographer's dream,
and only you can do it.


465
00:32:39.087 --> 00:32:41.671
- I wouldn't say that.
- No time for false modesty.


466
00:32:41.881 --> 00:32:44.758
You're the greatest, and we know it.
This is just your meat.


467
00:32:44.967 --> 00:32:49.554
A great classic theme.
The story of Faust in a modern setting.


468
00:32:51.432 --> 00:32:54.226
Say, that sounds interesting.

469
00:32:54.435 --> 00:32:57.187
I've never been so excited
about a project in my life.


470
00:32:57.396 --> 00:33:00.982
Now, there's Tony Hunter, myself,
a great score by the Martons.


471
00:33:01.192 --> 00:33:03.443
Wonderful. My brain's beginning
to churn already.


472
00:33:03.653 --> 00:33:07.405
Good. Now we must comb the country
for a wonderful singer for the girl.


473
00:33:07.698 --> 00:33:11.284
Singer? Jeff, don't you think we ought
to stress the dancing in that role?


474
00:33:11.494 --> 00:33:12.619
No, Paul.

475
00:33:12.829 --> 00:33:17.374
This girl has to be a virtuoso performer,
with fire, charm, beauty...


476
00:33:17.583 --> 00:33:21.545
...a great lady with a gamine quality.
You know no dancer can give you that.


477
00:33:21.754 --> 00:33:25.674
Wait. Of course I wouldn't let her do it,
but Gabrielle has all that and more.


478
00:33:25.883 --> 00:33:29.010
Gabrielle? Paul, 
I feel a little embarrassed.

479
00:33:29.220 --> 00:33:32.013
I think she's charming,
within her limitations. Charming.


480
00:33:32.223 --> 00:33:33.849
She's a great artist, and you know it.

481
00:33:34.058 --> 00:33:37.435
- Sorry. I know how fond of her you are.
- That has nothing to do with it!


482
00:33:37.645 --> 00:33:39.896
She can be one of the greatest
stars in the theater.


483
00:33:40.106 --> 00:33:41.481
Everybody's been trying to get her.

484
00:33:41.691 --> 00:33:43.817
For the right vehicle,
something light and fluffy.


485
00:33:44.026 --> 00:33:45.569
Light and fluffy? Now, see here, Jeff.

486
00:33:45.778 --> 00:33:49.197
I'm not gonna do this show
unless Gabrielle Gerard plays that part!


487
00:33:49.407 --> 00:33:53.034
Now, Paul, this throws a little
monkey wrench into things, doesn't it?


488
00:33:53.244 --> 00:33:56.079
Never mind.
You and I will work together sometime...


489
00:33:56.289 --> 00:33:59.416
Wait. At least do this. You come
and see her in the ballet tomorrow.


490
00:33:59.625 --> 00:34:02.002
- Bring Hunter, bring the Martons.
- No. Impossible.


491
00:34:02.211 --> 00:34:04.713
I have a performance.
But I'll gladly send the Martons.


492
00:34:04.922 --> 00:34:08.341
We can get together afterwards and talk.
Mind you, I'm promising nothing.


493
00:34:08.551 --> 00:34:10.302
Good night, sweetie.

494
00:34:12.722 --> 00:34:13.889
Drama desk?

495
00:34:14.098 --> 00:34:17.601
Mike. Hal again.
Better print that item after all.


496
00:34:17.810 --> 00:34:22.147
And, Mike, after this, if Mr. Cordova tells
you he's casting Tallulah...


497
00:34:22.356 --> 00:34:24.900
...for Little Eva, believe him.

498
00:35:44.188 --> 00:35:45.230
Well?

499
00:35:45.439 --> 00:35:48.525
She's fabulous, sensational,
loveliest thing I've ever seen.


500
00:36:25.229 --> 00:36:26.980
A little tall, isn't she?

501
00:36:28.065 --> 00:36:29.607
Stage illusion.

502
00:37:06.312 --> 00:37:07.979
So you didn't care for it much?

503
00:37:08.189 --> 00:37:09.981
The girl's fantastic, beautiful...

504
00:37:10.191 --> 00:37:11.566
...but I can't dance with her.

505
00:37:11.776 --> 00:37:13.234
Stop worrying!

506
00:37:16.781 --> 00:37:19.491
It isn't that I don't appreciate
what she does.


507
00:37:19.700 --> 00:37:22.494
I tell you, I know she's magnificent.
That's what scares me.


508
00:37:22.703 --> 00:37:26.331
But I haven't done ballet
since I was a kid. I'd look silly.


509
00:37:26.665 --> 00:37:29.334
Hello, Lil. You look wonderful.
Put your things over there.


510
00:37:29.543 --> 00:37:30.835
Hello, Mr. Hunter. How are you?

511
00:37:31.045 --> 00:37:32.879
- Hello, Les. Glad to see you.
- How are you?


512
00:37:33.089 --> 00:37:35.298
What is this?
The annual fur trappers' convention?


513
00:37:35.508 --> 00:37:37.634
- The boss is inside with big money.
- His backers?


514
00:37:37.843 --> 00:37:40.178
- They're raising money for the show.
- What show, ours?


515
00:37:40.388 --> 00:37:42.180
- Sure.
- He hasn't read the script yet.


516
00:37:42.390 --> 00:37:44.015
- I better go back...
- Sorry, Mr. Marton.


517
00:37:44.225 --> 00:37:47.268
You disturb the water, you scare the fish.
They're biting tonight.


518
00:37:47.478 --> 00:37:49.979
- What's he telling them?
- Whatever it is, it's going over big.


519
00:37:50.147 --> 00:37:51.815
- Come on, Lil.
- Please don't go in yet.


520
00:37:51.982 --> 00:37:53.608
Wait here.
He's saving you for the finale.


521
00:37:55.069 --> 00:37:56.111
Excuse me.

522
00:37:56.320 --> 00:37:58.196
- Lester, isn't this wonderful?
- Yeah.


523
00:37:58.406 --> 00:38:00.573
- This is going to be great, Tony.
- Why?


524
00:38:00.783 --> 00:38:02.909
Cordova. The dough for the show.
No problems.


525
00:38:03.119 --> 00:38:05.412
How many times did we have to audition
the last time?


526
00:38:05.621 --> 00:38:07.455
- Fifty.
- A hundred, maybe more.


527
00:38:07.665 --> 00:38:11.626
Jeff might raise the backing tonight.
We'll be ready to rehearse in three weeks.


528
00:38:12.920 --> 00:38:14.796
- Hello, Hal.
- Hello, Paul. How are you?


529
00:38:15.005 --> 00:38:16.548
How nice to see you. 
Come right in.

530
00:38:16.757 --> 00:38:18.675
Hal, this is Miss Gerard. Mr. Benton.

531
00:38:18.884 --> 00:38:20.969
How do you do?
Jeff's inside with the backers.


532
00:38:21.178 --> 00:38:22.971
Why don't you wait in the library?

533
00:38:23.180 --> 00:38:24.597
- Excuse me.
- Thanks.


534
00:38:29.395 --> 00:38:30.437
Paul.

535
00:38:31.021 --> 00:38:33.231
Let's wait in here a minute, huh?

536
00:38:34.400 --> 00:38:36.651
Now, wait a second. 
I'm not ready yet.

537
00:38:36.861 --> 00:38:38.611
There's a lot to be cleared up first.

538
00:38:38.821 --> 00:38:41.156
This girl Gerard, it's not just her dancing.

539
00:38:41.365 --> 00:38:44.617
On top of everything, she's too tall for me.
This girl is a giantess.


540
00:38:44.827 --> 00:38:46.786
She's not too tall for you. 
I know this girl.

541
00:38:46.996 --> 00:38:49.080
She comes up to here,
maybe 2 inches shorter.


542
00:38:49.290 --> 00:38:51.541
You know I'm the perfect height for you.
Now look...


543
00:38:51.750 --> 00:38:54.043
...turn around. Measure. Look.
You see? Isn't that fine?


544
00:38:54.253 --> 00:38:59.048
Listen. Gabrielle Gerard in her
stocking feet is at the most 3-feet tall.


545
00:38:59.508 --> 00:39:03.344
Now relax. I'm going to find you a drink,
and you can stop worrying about her.


546
00:39:03.554 --> 00:39:06.139
Jeff only wants her in the show
because she's the best.


547
00:39:06.348 --> 00:39:08.683
We all gotta go along
with him too, Tony.


548
00:39:08.893 --> 00:39:10.935
In the show, one guy's got to be
at the helm...


549
00:39:11.145 --> 00:39:13.563
...and in Jeff, we got someone
we can trust to...


550
00:39:13.772 --> 00:39:17.275
...it is the Devil, come to claim the soul
of the modern Faust man.


551
00:39:17.485 --> 00:39:20.278
With flapping wings
and grinning evil eyes...


552
00:39:20.488 --> 00:39:23.239
...he points the way
to the yawning pits of Hades.


553
00:39:26.827 --> 00:39:27.952
Hallelujah.

554
00:39:29.163 --> 00:39:31.331
- I'm embarrassed.
- Don't be childish.


555
00:39:31.540 --> 00:39:33.958
I'm sure Tony Hunter doesn't want me
in this show.


556
00:39:34.168 --> 00:39:36.920
- What makes you say that?
- Did he come backstage to see me...


557
00:39:37.129 --> 00:39:38.171
...after the performance?

558
00:39:38.380 --> 00:39:40.173
He knew he was
going to meet you here.

559
00:39:40.382 --> 00:39:44.093
- I'm just a ballet dancer...
- You're a famous leading ballerina.


560
00:39:44.303 --> 00:39:47.514
What does he want with me?
He's a famous movie and stage actor.


561
00:39:47.723 --> 00:39:50.350
He's practically a historical character
by now.


562
00:39:50.559 --> 00:39:53.853
Dancing with him is like dancing
with a statue of General Grant.


563
00:39:54.063 --> 00:39:55.563
Now look, Gaby.

564
00:39:55.981 --> 00:39:59.484
You know, this is a Cordova show.
It's an important step for you.


565
00:39:59.693 --> 00:40:03.655
I'm going to do the choreography,
so there's nothing for you to worry about.


566
00:40:03.864 --> 00:40:06.658
But I still think he doesn't want me
in the show.


567
00:40:06.867 --> 00:40:08.201
Your nose is shiny.

568
00:40:08.410 --> 00:40:10.620
- Where's the, uh?
- Maybe this is it.


569
00:40:12.206 --> 00:40:16.918
He passes by all the writhing souls
in torment paying for their deadly sins.


570
00:40:17.127 --> 00:40:18.920
Gluttony, avarice...

571
00:40:20.881 --> 00:40:22.382
It must be upstairs.

572
00:40:40.150 --> 00:40:41.943
Lester, what have we got ourselves into?

573
00:40:42.152 --> 00:40:45.488
The story he's telling them has nothing
to do with the story we wrote.


574
00:40:45.698 --> 00:40:48.116
This will mean months of rewriting.

575
00:40:48.325 --> 00:40:51.536
He expects us to go into rehearsal
in three weeks?


576
00:40:55.791 --> 00:41:00.545
Brimstone and flames. Save me.

577
00:41:07.720 --> 00:41:12.557
Corrupter of children.
Purveyor of evil. Dungeon...


578
00:41:14.059 --> 00:41:18.479
...bubbling cauldrons.
Fiery furnaces of doom.


579
00:41:26.572 --> 00:41:28.948
- You're...
- And you're... How do you do?


580
00:41:29.158 --> 00:41:30.825
How do you do? 
It's certainly a...

581
00:41:31.035 --> 00:41:33.953
- We've been waiting for you in there.
- We just got here.


582
00:41:34.163 --> 00:41:36.372
We just got here ourselves,
about five minutes ago.


583
00:41:36.582 --> 00:41:38.583
A little early, I guess. Mr. 
Cordova's busy.

584
00:41:38.792 --> 00:41:41.210
Yes, I know, and I
rushed so to get here.

585
00:41:41.420 --> 00:41:43.880
- I'm a mess.
- No. You look wonderful.


586
00:41:45.424 --> 00:41:48.468
- Will you have a cigarette?
- No, thanks. I don't smoke.


587
00:41:48.677 --> 00:41:51.638
- Never?
- I don't think a dancer should smoke.


588
00:41:51.847 --> 00:41:52.972
I see.

589
00:41:54.099 --> 00:41:56.976
- Is anything wrong?
- No.


590
00:41:57.728 --> 00:41:59.771
- Pretty shoes.
- Thank you.


591
00:42:00.064 --> 00:42:01.648
You always wear high heels?

592
00:42:01.857 --> 00:42:04.317
No. Not always. 
Sometimes toe shoes.

593
00:42:04.818 --> 00:42:06.110
Toe shoes.

594
00:42:06.320 --> 00:42:08.154
I'm afraid I've been awfully rude.

595
00:42:08.364 --> 00:42:10.865
I haven't told you how wonderful
you were tonight.


596
00:42:11.075 --> 00:42:13.743
Thank you.
I'm a great admirer of yours too.


597
00:42:13.952 --> 00:42:16.621
- I didn't think you'd ever even heard of me.
- Heard of you?


598
00:42:16.830 --> 00:42:19.457
I used to see all your pictures
when I was a little girl.


599
00:42:19.667 --> 00:42:23.127
I'm still a fan. I recently went to see
a revival of them at the museum.


600
00:42:23.337 --> 00:42:24.379
Museum?

601
00:42:24.588 --> 00:42:26.339
"Step right this way,
ladies and gentlemen.


602
00:42:26.548 --> 00:42:28.341
"Egyptian mummies, extinct reptiles...

603
00:42:28.550 --> 00:42:31.177
...and Tony Hunter,
the grand old man of the dance."


604
00:42:31.387 --> 00:42:32.428
I didn't mean...

605
00:42:32.638 --> 00:42:36.474
I want you to know that I can still
thread a needle without my eyeglasses...


606
00:42:36.684 --> 00:42:39.394
...and still occasionally do
a soft-shoe shuffle.


607
00:42:39.603 --> 00:42:41.062
Nothing balletic, of course.

608
00:42:41.271 --> 00:42:43.064
You're not a ballet devotee, are you?

609
00:42:43.273 --> 00:42:45.775
Yes. I was going to the ballet
before you were born.


610
00:42:45.984 --> 00:42:49.028
I saw Pavlova, Karsavina,
all the real ballet greats.


611
00:42:49.238 --> 00:42:51.823
You don't see dancing like that nowadays.
I'm sorry.


612
00:42:52.032 --> 00:42:54.575
That's okay. I don't expect you
to class me with Pavlova.


613
00:42:54.785 --> 00:42:55.952
In fact, if she were around...

614
00:42:56.161 --> 00:42:58.287
...I doubt if she'd be good enough
to dance with you.


615
00:42:58.497 --> 00:43:00.456
You'd probably insist on an audition first.

616
00:43:00.666 --> 00:43:03.292
I sure would.
I'd audition my own grandmother.


617
00:43:03.502 --> 00:43:07.004
Then why don't you audition mine?
She'd be just about right for you.


618
00:43:07.214 --> 00:43:09.257
- I'm terribly sorry.
- No, you're not.


619
00:43:09.466 --> 00:43:10.842
- No, I'm not.
- Neither am I.


620
00:43:11.051 --> 00:43:12.093
Good.

621
00:43:16.807 --> 00:43:19.517
- Paul, I'm leaving.
- What's the matter, darling?


622
00:43:19.727 --> 00:43:21.769
I can't work with that man.
He's impossible.


623
00:43:21.979 --> 00:43:23.563
We just got here. 
It'll look funny...

624
00:43:23.772 --> 00:43:26.357
The whole thing is off.
This girl is a monster.


625
00:43:26.567 --> 00:43:28.443
I have definitely had it.

626
00:43:29.903 --> 00:43:33.948
And now, ladies and gentlemen,
the brains, the talent, the artists.


627
00:43:34.575 --> 00:43:36.993
Wonderful. Aren't they wonderful?

628
00:43:43.417 --> 00:43:45.585
You have no idea
how well things are going.


629
00:43:45.794 --> 00:43:47.503
It's really wonderful.

630
00:43:48.589 --> 00:43:50.381
Ladies and gentlemen.

631
00:43:50.591 --> 00:43:52.884
I want you all to meet
the happy little group...


632
00:43:53.051 --> 00:43:54.510
...that's responsible for the show...

633
00:43:54.720 --> 00:43:57.847
...that everyone will be clamoring
to get seats for next season.


634
00:43:58.056 --> 00:44:00.683
The celebrated choreographer Paul Byrd.

635
00:44:03.228 --> 00:44:07.315
The authors you know:
Lily and Lester Marton.


636
00:44:07.524 --> 00:44:09.192
Take a bow, Lily.

637
00:44:09.818 --> 00:44:11.694
And, ladies and gentlemen...

638
00:44:11.904 --> 00:44:14.030
...my star, Tony Hunter.

639
00:44:14.239 --> 00:44:17.658
A name, a talent.
Mr. Show Business himself.


640
00:44:20.370 --> 00:44:23.539
And, ladies and gentlemen,
his new leading lady.


641
00:44:23.749 --> 00:44:27.710
That glamorous, delightful dancer
from the magical world of ballet.


642
00:44:27.920 --> 00:44:31.923
Mr. Hunter's own personal choice,
Gabrielle Gerard.


643
00:44:34.426 --> 00:44:38.012
I think, gentlemen, you will agree
your investment is safe, yes?


644
00:44:38.222 --> 00:44:41.015
Now let's relax and
have a drink, shall we?

645
00:44:42.601 --> 00:44:46.521
My dear, how do you authors
ever think of these brilliant ideas?


646
00:44:46.730 --> 00:44:49.816
That damnation scene.
Did you ever in your life hear...


647
00:44:50.025 --> 00:44:53.986
My boy. I had the pleasure
of backing your last show too.


648
00:44:54.404 --> 00:44:57.156
Jeffrey. How about?

649
00:45:12.464 --> 00:45:14.924
There it is, folks. 
The work light.

650
00:45:15.133 --> 00:45:17.969
Only an electric bulb, perhaps,
but for the next four weeks...


651
00:45:18.178 --> 00:45:20.930
...that will be our
sun, our moon, our stars.

652
00:45:21.139 --> 00:45:24.433
These four walls will be our universe,
our private world.


653
00:45:24.643 --> 00:45:27.770
We enter with nothing but a dream,
but when we leave...


654
00:45:27.980 --> 00:45:29.564
...we'll have a show.

655
00:45:29.773 --> 00:45:34.026
In between, there will be enthusiasms,
frustrations, hot tempers...


656
00:45:34.236 --> 00:45:35.444
...ha, ha, cold coffee.

657
00:45:35.654 --> 00:45:38.155
Some of us will
fight, some fall in love...

658
00:45:38.365 --> 00:45:40.741
...but all of us
will work and adore it...

659
00:45:40.951 --> 00:45:43.786
...because all of us are inspired
by the same thing.


660
00:45:43.996 --> 00:45:47.707
The night that curtain goes up,
it will go up on a smash hit.


661
00:45:47.916 --> 00:45:49.792
And believe me, kids...

662
00:45:50.043 --> 00:45:53.004
...there's nothing in the world as soothing...

663
00:45:53.213 --> 00:45:55.131
...as a smash hit.

664
00:46:47.935 --> 00:46:50.978
What do you think this is,
summer stock or something?


665
00:47:12.376 --> 00:47:13.417
Go!

666
00:47:14.920 --> 00:47:19.215
That's it. That's wonderful.
Why didn't you do it before?


667
00:47:19.424 --> 00:47:20.800
Good, men.

668
00:47:21.009 --> 00:47:23.552
Honey, would you try
that cross, please, again for me?


669
00:47:23.762 --> 00:47:26.889
"The same kind of opportunistic snake
that he is."


670
00:47:27.140 --> 00:47:29.850
"You got me wrong. 
I'm a self-made snake.

671
00:47:30.060 --> 00:47:33.312
"Listen, baby, we all live by the jungle:
Eat or be eaten.


672
00:47:33.522 --> 00:47:37.566
"I just realized that I like to eat,
and to eat caviar whenever possible.


673
00:47:37.776 --> 00:47:39.819
"Anything wrong with that?"

674
00:47:40.153 --> 00:47:42.822
"Anything wrong with that?" A bad line.

675
00:47:43.031 --> 00:47:47.493
What we need is some quick image,
like "spreading ideals on a cracker."


676
00:47:47.703 --> 00:47:50.538
You all like that?
"Ever try spreading ideals on a cracker?"


677
00:47:50.747 --> 00:47:52.081
Let me hear it, Tony.

678
00:47:52.290 --> 00:47:54.583
Did you ever try spreading ideals
on a cracker?


679
00:47:54.793 --> 00:47:57.545
- Jeff. I don't...
- Honey, just try that cross again for me.


680
00:47:57.754 --> 00:48:00.881
"The same kind of opportunistic snake
that he is."


681
00:48:01.508 --> 00:48:04.093
"You got me wrong. 
I'm a self-made snake.

682
00:48:04.302 --> 00:48:07.013
"Listen, baby.
We all live by the law of the jungle..."


683
00:48:07.222 --> 00:48:09.015
- Excuse me, Tony.
- "...eat or be eaten."


684
00:48:09.224 --> 00:48:10.808
Pardon me, folks.

685
00:48:17.899 --> 00:48:19.608
You know about icebergs, don't you?

686
00:48:19.818 --> 00:48:22.653
One-eighth above the surface,
seven-eighths below. That's you.


687
00:48:22.863 --> 00:48:25.740
You're giving me only that one-eighth.
I'm greedy. I want more.


688
00:48:25.949 --> 00:48:27.616
All eight-eighths. Now let it rip, Tony.

689
00:48:27.826 --> 00:48:31.912
Give it too much. Go way over.
Come along. The whole eight-eighths!


690
00:48:32.205 --> 00:48:33.497
Okay, Gaby. Same place.

691
00:48:33.707 --> 00:48:35.833
"The same kind of opportunistic snake
that he is."


692
00:48:36.043 --> 00:48:37.960
You got me wrong. 
I'm a self-made snake!

693
00:48:38.170 --> 00:48:41.297
Listen, baby. We all live by
the law of the jungle: Eat or be eaten!


694
00:48:41.506 --> 00:48:45.176
And I realized that I like to eat,
and eat caviar whenever possible.


695
00:48:45.385 --> 00:48:48.137
Did you ever try spreading ideals
on a cracker?


696
00:48:48.346 --> 00:48:51.098
Good boy, Tony. That's it. 
Eight-eighths.

697
00:49:03.528 --> 00:49:05.988
- Sorry. Butterfingers.
- No. It's not your fault, Tony.


698
00:49:06.198 --> 00:49:08.115
It's an awkward pattern.
I have a better idea.


699
00:49:08.325 --> 00:49:10.493
You hold your position right here,
and Jimmy...


700
00:49:10.702 --> 00:49:13.996
...suppose you pick up Gaby like that,
and put her down...


701
00:49:14.206 --> 00:49:16.248
...right here next to Tony?
Now you see, Tony...


702
00:49:16.458 --> 00:49:18.667
I'd like to practice it with her
two or three times.


703
00:49:18.877 --> 00:49:19.919
I think I could handle it.

704
00:49:20.128 --> 00:49:21.796
Do you mind if
he tries it with Barbara?

705
00:49:22.005 --> 00:49:23.798
These are new toe shoes.
They're killing me.


706
00:49:24.007 --> 00:49:26.509
Sure. You go ahead and rest.
Barbara, come here. Try it.


707
00:49:26.718 --> 00:49:28.719
I think this is what's throwing you off.

708
00:49:28.929 --> 00:49:32.014
If you hold your balance so, like this,
then grab her here by the...


709
00:49:32.224 --> 00:49:34.975
Paul, I think we're making a mistake here.

710
00:49:38.647 --> 00:49:40.481
I think we're wasting Tony in this scene.

711
00:49:40.690 --> 00:49:43.818
He's got the first-act finale right after this.
The damnation scene.


712
00:49:44.027 --> 00:49:46.028
I don't want to dissipate
his impact in that.


713
00:49:46.238 --> 00:49:50.407
Now, why not let him exit into the house
and watch it from his balcony?


714
00:49:50.617 --> 00:49:52.034
- How'd that be?
- Wonderful idea.


715
00:49:52.244 --> 00:49:54.620
See what that would do?
Save your sock for the finale.


716
00:49:54.830 --> 00:49:55.913
Much better that way.

717
00:49:56.123 --> 00:49:58.290
Let's go back
to the beginning positions. Gaby.


718
00:49:58.500 --> 00:50:00.376
Boys, get around up here,
and the girls, yes.


719
00:50:00.585 --> 00:50:03.045
You were down here in the line like that.
Not too close.


720
00:50:03.255 --> 00:50:04.964
This group's down here,
you're up there.


721
00:50:05.173 --> 00:50:06.799
- Let's try it this way.
- No!


722
00:50:07.008 --> 00:50:09.844
Let's not try it this
way or any other way.

723
00:50:11.596 --> 00:50:15.641
I have had enough. I've had
three weeks of these lovely rehearsals...


724
00:50:15.851 --> 00:50:19.228
...three weeks of Chinese torture.
I don't know what you're trying to do...


725
00:50:19.437 --> 00:50:22.022
...except make me look like a complete fool.
A clumsy idiot.


726
00:50:22.232 --> 00:50:25.442
I've tried. For three weeks, I've tried.
I've taken everything.


727
00:50:25.652 --> 00:50:29.196
I've watched my part being changed,
my numbers being cut out day after day...


728
00:50:29.364 --> 00:50:30.531
...and I haven't said a word.

729
00:50:30.740 --> 00:50:33.075
Got to be cooperative,
think of the good of the show.


730
00:50:33.285 --> 00:50:35.202
Let's get this straight:

731
00:50:35.579 --> 00:50:39.165
I am not Nijinsky. 
I am not Marlon Brando.

732
00:50:39.374 --> 00:50:42.710
I am Mrs. Hunter's little boy, Tony,
song-and-dance man.


733
00:50:42.919 --> 00:50:45.838
I'm supposed to have entertained
millions of people in my time.


734
00:50:46.047 --> 00:50:50.759
And I am not entertained by
this little ballerina's snide insinuations...


735
00:50:50.969 --> 00:50:52.720
...that I am a no-talent hoofer.

736
00:50:52.929 --> 00:50:55.848
I am sick of her superior smirk.
I'm sick of her.


737
00:50:56.057 --> 00:50:59.894
I'm sick of Faust. I am sick of this show.
Never mind saying it!


738
00:51:00.103 --> 00:51:02.855
Tony Hunter, 1953.

739
00:51:03.315 --> 00:51:05.691
I hereby declare my independence.

740
00:51:05.901 --> 00:51:09.111
Tony Hunter, 1776.

741
00:51:09.487 --> 00:51:10.821
Bless you.

742
00:51:25.670 --> 00:51:28.380
- Lester, where are you going?
- I don't know. I was...


743
00:51:28.590 --> 00:51:32.718
What's happening to us? Let's try
to keep our heads. It's only a show.


744
00:51:32.928 --> 00:51:34.595
I know. I'm sorry, baby.

745
00:51:34.804 --> 00:51:37.848
So am I. Let's try
to be sensible about it.

746
00:51:38.058 --> 00:51:41.852
- Do you think we should try to find Tony?
- I don't know. What do you think?


747
00:51:42.062 --> 00:51:44.230
- Maybe we should.
- But Jeff said not to.


748
00:51:44.439 --> 00:51:46.982
And, of course,
you mustn't disobey teacher.


749
00:51:47.192 --> 00:51:50.152
Right or wrong,
someone has got to be at the helm.


750
00:51:50.362 --> 00:51:52.821
But to you, he's
100 percent right every time.

751
00:51:53.031 --> 00:51:56.408
If you say one more word to me
about Jeff's hypnotic influence on me...


752
00:51:56.618 --> 00:51:58.452
...I'll scream.
- He's got you so bulldozed...


753
00:52:00.038 --> 00:52:01.747
Someone's liable to think we're quarreling.

754
00:52:01.915 --> 00:52:03.999
We're not quarreling.
We're in complete agreement.


755
00:52:04.209 --> 00:52:05.918
- We hate each other.
- Unh!


756
00:52:16.596 --> 00:52:20.808
Joe, tell Mrs. 
Marton I've gone to Tahiti...

757
00:52:21.393 --> 00:52:22.643
...to paint.

758
00:52:56.761 --> 00:53:00.097
- Hello, Mr. Hunter.
- You must have the wrong apartment.


759
00:53:00.307 --> 00:53:03.434
No. I came to see you.
May I come in a minute?


760
00:53:03.643 --> 00:53:04.810
Please.

761
00:53:06.229 --> 00:53:09.940
I, uh, was just about to slip
into my bed of nails.


762
00:53:13.737 --> 00:53:14.778
Oh.

763
00:53:16.072 --> 00:53:17.406
I'm terribly sorry.

764
00:53:17.615 --> 00:53:21.535
That's all right. You couldn't have done it
if I hadn't softened it up for you.


765
00:53:21.745 --> 00:53:23.203
- What?
- Nothing.


766
00:53:24.164 --> 00:53:25.581
- Cigarette?
- No, thanks.


767
00:53:25.790 --> 00:53:27.916
That's right. Dancers shouldn't smoke.

768
00:53:28.126 --> 00:53:30.919
- You mind if I do?
- Yes. I mean, it's all right.


769
00:53:31.129 --> 00:53:32.296
Thanks.

770
00:53:36.176 --> 00:53:37.509
How lovely.

771
00:53:38.511 --> 00:53:41.472
I've never seen such wonderful prints
in a hotel.


772
00:53:41.681 --> 00:53:44.725
They don't belong to the hotel yet.
They're mine, and they're originals.


773
00:53:44.934 --> 00:53:45.976
Oh.

774
00:53:46.186 --> 00:53:47.269
Don't let that throw you.

775
00:53:47.479 --> 00:53:51.440
I don't know any more about art than I do
about dancing. I'm just a Hollywood actor.


776
00:53:51.649 --> 00:53:53.859
I call my agent and say,
"I've got a wall to cover.


777
00:53:54.069 --> 00:53:57.529
"Send me over 20 feet's worth of paintings
in assorted colors."


778
00:53:59.240 --> 00:54:01.784
That's a very early Degas, isn't it?

779
00:54:02.786 --> 00:54:04.620
"1877."

780
00:54:06.373 --> 00:54:10.125
Yeah. I swiped it from his desk in school.
Was he sore.


781
00:54:13.380 --> 00:54:14.630
What can I do for you?

782
00:54:14.839 --> 00:54:18.133
I know. You demand an apology.
Okay, let's cut it short. I apologize.


783
00:54:18.343 --> 00:54:21.428
No, don't do that.
I'm supposed to apologize to you.


784
00:54:22.013 --> 00:54:23.138
- Oh...
- I mean...


785
00:54:23.348 --> 00:54:26.016
I see, the fellows got together,
stuck a gun in your back...


786
00:54:26.226 --> 00:54:29.228
No, it was all my idea.
I just wanted to tell you that...


787
00:54:29.437 --> 00:54:31.563
All right. It was Paul's idea.

788
00:54:31.773 --> 00:54:33.565
Why do I let him push me around?

789
00:54:33.775 --> 00:54:36.360
What do I want to apologize
to you for anyway?


790
00:54:36.569 --> 00:54:38.320
You've been mean to me.

791
00:54:38.530 --> 00:54:41.740
You didn't want me in the show
in the first place.


792
00:54:41.950 --> 00:54:42.991
What?

793
00:54:43.201 --> 00:54:45.661
And you think
I'm a dime-a-dozen ballet dancer.


794
00:54:45.870 --> 00:54:46.912
No.

795
00:54:47.122 --> 00:54:50.541
And this whole thing's making me
a nervous wreck and no show is worth it.


796
00:54:50.750 --> 00:54:53.752
I wouldn't apologize to you
in a million years.


797
00:54:53.962 --> 00:54:58.048
Now, don't do that. Please, just
calm down. Now take it easy. Look.


798
00:54:58.258 --> 00:55:00.843
I thought I was the only nervous wreck
around here...


799
00:55:01.052 --> 00:55:02.845
...and all this time you've been behaving...

800
00:55:03.054 --> 00:55:05.681
I've behaved horribly to
you, and I know it.

801
00:55:05.890 --> 00:55:09.726
I'm not used to behaving horribly.
It's a big strain.


802
00:55:10.728 --> 00:55:14.106
You just misunderstood me, that's all.
I think you're terrific.


803
00:55:14.315 --> 00:55:17.860
I think everything in the show
is probably terrific, except me.


804
00:55:18.069 --> 00:55:20.279
I've been scared to death of you...

805
00:55:20.488 --> 00:55:23.740
...and scared to death
of every last kid in the chorus.


806
00:55:26.953 --> 00:55:28.787
Don't be nice to me.

807
00:55:29.873 --> 00:55:32.916
It just makes me seem twice as ugly.

808
00:55:36.296 --> 00:55:39.840
I'd say you were more plain than ugly...

809
00:55:40.175 --> 00:55:42.885
...but at least you've got talent.
- Thanks.


810
00:55:43.636 --> 00:55:45.804
Now look, Gaby. 
It's just plain silly...

811
00:55:46.014 --> 00:55:48.223
...that we have never sat down
and talked this out.


812
00:55:48.433 --> 00:55:51.518
We are the only animals given
the greatest means of communication...


813
00:55:51.728 --> 00:55:52.769
...human speech.

814
00:55:52.979 --> 00:55:56.190
- And all we do is snarl at each other.
- I know.


815
00:55:56.399 --> 00:55:59.234
We're from two different worlds,
two eras...


816
00:55:59.444 --> 00:56:02.404
...but yet we're supposed
to dance together, work together.


817
00:56:02.614 --> 00:56:04.156
No one consulted us...

818
00:56:04.365 --> 00:56:07.493
...but we're the only things that matter
in this whole thing.


819
00:56:07.827 --> 00:56:11.163
Not those geniuses out there,
telling us what to do.


820
00:56:11.664 --> 00:56:15.167
You're right.
We have to do the performing.


821
00:56:15.710 --> 00:56:18.170
We're the ones
that have to get up on that stage...


822
00:56:18.379 --> 00:56:22.716
...and make idiots out of ourselves.
- Tony, is that what's going to happen?


823
00:56:22.926 --> 00:56:25.928
No. Of course not.
Things are going to be fine.


824
00:56:26.137 --> 00:56:29.556
I have a feeling that everything
is going to be much better from now on.


825
00:56:29.766 --> 00:56:31.475
Yes, I know, but...

826
00:56:33.186 --> 00:56:35.729
Can you and I really dance together?

827
00:56:36.606 --> 00:56:38.065
I don't know.

828
00:56:39.192 --> 00:56:40.692
Let's find out.

829
00:56:46.032 --> 00:56:47.991
- Taxi, sir?
- Yes, please.


830
00:56:53.665 --> 00:56:55.624
- El Morocco, please.
- No.


831
00:56:56.334 --> 00:56:57.459
Stork? Waldorf?

832
00:56:57.669 --> 00:57:00.170
No. I'm not dressed.
I just came from rehearsal.


833
00:57:00.380 --> 00:57:03.090
- I can't go to any of those places.
- You look fine to me.


834
00:57:03.299 --> 00:57:05.509
- Never mind. Thanks.
- Thank you.


835
00:57:11.224 --> 00:57:14.226
- Where to, sir?
- Leave it to the horse.


836
00:57:23.945 --> 00:57:25.737
Look, trees.

837
00:57:26.447 --> 00:57:29.408
Yes, I remember now, dimly. Trees.

838
00:57:30.368 --> 00:57:32.494
And isn't that called grass?

839
00:57:33.371 --> 00:57:35.414
And, look, there's the sky.

840
00:57:36.249 --> 00:57:37.708
This has all been here...

841
00:57:37.917 --> 00:57:41.295
...the whole time we have been
shut up in our little sweatbox of the arts.


842
00:57:41.504 --> 00:57:43.255
Really? Amazing.

843
00:57:43.715 --> 00:57:47.009
Do you know what those are
on those benches? People.


844
00:57:47.343 --> 00:57:48.427
Happy people.

845
00:57:48.636 --> 00:57:50.554
Would you believe it?
They don't even care...


846
00:57:50.763 --> 00:57:54.057
...whether we have a damnation scene
in our show or not.


847
00:57:55.560 --> 00:57:57.019
Neither do I.

848
01:02:41.178 --> 01:02:42.971
You can't get it into the elevators.

849
01:02:43.180 --> 01:02:46.641
And you take this one here,
and it won't fit the finale.


850
01:02:46.851 --> 01:02:49.269
- How are we doing?
- It's a disaster.


851
01:02:49.478 --> 01:02:52.439
We're in terrible trouble.
We just can't open in three days.


852
01:02:52.648 --> 01:02:56.192
I told you from the beginning,
you are overloading the show.


853
01:02:56.402 --> 01:02:58.653
You can't get all this scenery
in the theater.


854
01:02:58.863 --> 01:03:01.698
- Why isn't this hung?
- We've been hanging all night.


855
01:03:01.908 --> 01:03:04.242
You've got more scenery in this show...

856
01:03:04.452 --> 01:03:06.536
...than there is in Yellowstone National Park.

857
01:03:06.746 --> 01:03:09.497
Never mind. Get your blueprints.
We'll go have a conference.


858
01:03:09.707 --> 01:03:12.125
Everything will work out all right.

859
01:03:17.006 --> 01:03:20.258
Hold it. I scored for brass,
and all I hear is flute.


860
01:03:20.468 --> 01:03:22.052
I don't want so many long bows.

861
01:03:22.261 --> 01:03:25.221
Lester, I gotta cut 16 bars
out of that dance.


862
01:03:25.806 --> 01:03:27.682
Sixteen bars! Hey, Lil.

863
01:03:28.225 --> 01:03:31.019
All right, I'll make
the cut. Page to page.

864
01:03:31.228 --> 01:03:33.605
Would you ask Lily
if she approves the cut?


865
01:03:33.814 --> 01:03:36.066
- Lil, how about this cut?
- It's fine.


866
01:03:36.275 --> 01:03:37.901
Okay, Lester. Let's give it to her.

867
01:03:38.110 --> 01:03:41.279
This'll sound like hash.
I better put some chords in for transition.


868
01:03:41.489 --> 01:03:44.658
Wait, just a minute.
Sublime, time, dime, slime...


869
01:03:44.867 --> 01:03:46.868
You can't hear Tony in Lovelier Than You.

870
01:03:47.078 --> 01:03:50.664
- I'm already holding down the orchestra.
- Maybe the key's too low.


871
01:03:51.374 --> 01:03:53.625
Ask Lester if Tony can
take it a key higher.

872
01:03:53.834 --> 01:03:55.710
About Lovelier Than You,
Les, a key higher?


873
01:03:55.920 --> 01:03:58.505
Don't you see I'm trying to make a cut?
The key's perfect.


874
01:03:58.714 --> 01:04:02.050
- But Lily said you'd make the change.
- The key is...


875
01:04:05.429 --> 01:04:08.056
Everyone on their toes
for the transformation scene.


876
01:04:08.265 --> 01:04:10.934
- We're not ready.
- Perfectly all right. Next.


877
01:04:11.143 --> 01:04:13.186
Watch it.
I'll cue you for the transition music.


878
01:04:13.396 --> 01:04:14.980
Isn't it great? Herman.

879
01:04:15.189 --> 01:04:16.940
Everybody ready back there?

880
01:04:17.149 --> 01:04:19.192
We got to have more time
to make the change.


881
01:04:19.402 --> 01:04:22.821
- I've got to have 16 more men.
- I got elevators...


882
01:04:23.030 --> 01:04:24.072
Do the best you can.

883
01:04:24.281 --> 01:04:25.865
All right, everybody. This is it.

884
01:04:26.075 --> 01:04:28.827
Men in the elevators,
watch the signal lights for your cues.


885
01:04:29.036 --> 01:04:32.080
Switchboards. Stand by to come down
your number one batten on cue.


886
01:04:32.289 --> 01:04:35.125
Girls on stairs, take your positions,
but don't be frightened.


887
01:04:35.334 --> 01:04:37.502
Men in armor, light your chandeliers.

888
01:04:37.712 --> 01:04:41.923
All right, make this great, everybody.
Don't forget, it's the first-act finale.


889
01:04:43.551 --> 01:04:46.261
Are you guys all right in there?
Now, watch your cue.


890
01:04:47.513 --> 01:04:48.888
Light change.

891
01:04:49.098 --> 01:04:50.265
Revolve.

892
01:04:54.895 --> 01:04:57.147
This is going to be beautiful.

893
01:04:57.565 --> 01:05:00.108
It will be a memorable moment.

894
01:05:00.484 --> 01:05:01.818
Memorable.

895
01:05:02.445 --> 01:05:03.695
Ah, yes.

896
01:05:03.904 --> 01:05:05.822
This is real theater.

897
01:05:06.032 --> 01:05:09.534
Everything's smooth as silk.

898
01:05:12.163 --> 01:05:16.833
No, Herman, that doesn't go up,
it goes down. Take it down.


899
01:05:17.668 --> 01:05:19.627
What is this? Herman!

900
01:05:20.296 --> 01:05:22.922
I don't think
you've got your cues right!


901
01:05:23.132 --> 01:05:24.674
No, stop!

902
01:05:25.176 --> 01:05:29.304
That one doesn't go down, it goes up.
Take it up.


903
01:05:30.765 --> 01:05:33.600
For heaven's sake, look at your cue sheet.

904
01:05:35.811 --> 01:05:39.939
Take it up. No, not me.

905
01:05:40.900 --> 01:05:43.943
Herman, this cable has fouled.

906
01:05:57.958 --> 01:05:59.751
Calm down. Don't let us lose our heads.

907
01:05:59.960 --> 01:06:02.629
This is a setback,
but that's what we come out of town for.


908
01:06:02.838 --> 01:06:03.880
We'll never make it work.

909
01:06:04.090 --> 01:06:07.383
Of course it will. You boys get together,
think of something brilliant.


910
01:06:07.593 --> 01:06:10.720
You can't put Gaby on that thing.
It's dangerous. I won't allow it.


911
01:06:10.930 --> 01:06:13.848
It's all right. After all, we expected
to strike a snag or two.


912
01:06:14.058 --> 01:06:16.810
Get the full company in the lounge
for dialogue rehearsal...


913
01:06:17.019 --> 01:06:20.647
...while they're clearing the stage.
We can't afford to waste a moment.


914
01:06:38.541 --> 01:06:41.209
Here. I'm sorry. I forgot.

915
01:06:47.591 --> 01:06:49.050
That help?

916
01:06:49.969 --> 01:06:51.469
All right?

917
01:06:54.807 --> 01:06:56.766
If you've quite finished, let's try this.

918
01:06:56.976 --> 01:06:59.519
We're going to get the stage soon.
You don't know it yet.


919
01:06:59.728 --> 01:07:04.357
Paul, I'm afraid Gaby's kind of beat.
Nobody's had any sleep for two nights.


920
01:07:04.567 --> 01:07:05.900
Can't you let her rest a while?

921
01:07:06.110 --> 01:07:08.778
If you don't mind, Tony,
I've worked with her for many years.


922
01:07:08.988 --> 01:07:11.322
I happen to know her a good deal
better than you do.


923
01:07:11.532 --> 01:07:12.782
All right, Gaby. Come on.

924
01:07:12.992 --> 01:07:14.492
Madame, may I have this dance?

925
01:07:14.702 --> 01:07:17.662
Cut the clowning. It's not going to seem
so funny tomorrow night.


926
01:07:17.872 --> 01:07:19.205
All right, Adam.

927
01:07:28.549 --> 01:07:32.093
Okay, Paul, they're ready for you on-stage.
Come on.


928
01:07:37.141 --> 01:07:40.894
This is the big moment.
Hal, come on. Take it over there.


929
01:07:41.103 --> 01:07:45.148
Tony, Gaby, this is it.
I want it to be outstanding.


930
01:07:45.524 --> 01:07:50.653
It must be beautiful, fabulous,
warm, and fiery.


931
01:07:54.074 --> 01:07:56.951
Your cue is, "Dance, fools, dance!"

932
01:07:58.746 --> 01:08:04.459
You and the night and the music

933
01:08:04.627 --> 01:08:07.045
Fill me with flaming desire

934
01:08:10.591 --> 01:08:15.386
Setting my being completely

935
01:08:15.554 --> 01:08:21.184
On fire, fire, fire

936
01:08:21.352 --> 01:08:24.062
You and the night and the music

937
01:08:26.690 --> 01:08:30.026
Thrill me but will we

938
01:08:30.194 --> 01:08:32.445
Be one

939
01:08:33.822 --> 01:08:37.700
After the night and the music

940
01:08:37.868 --> 01:08:42.247
Are done?

941
01:08:42.414 --> 01:08:45.667
Until the pale light

942
01:08:45.834 --> 01:08:48.544
Of dawning and daylight

943
01:08:48.712 --> 01:08:53.049
Our hearts will be throbbing guitars

944
01:08:56.345 --> 01:09:00.265
Hal, it seems to be a little too much,
doesn't it?


945
01:09:01.433 --> 01:09:02.684
Yes.

946
01:09:04.687 --> 01:09:07.689
Are we really supposed
to open tomorrow night?


947
01:09:13.237 --> 01:09:15.530
"Dance, fools, dance!"

948
01:09:37.803 --> 01:09:40.513
Hello, there! It's a big night.

949
01:09:42.766 --> 01:09:46.060
Everybody is here from New York.
Simply everybody.


950
01:09:46.270 --> 01:09:49.188
Do you hear that, my dear?
Everybody from New York is here.


951
01:09:50.065 --> 01:09:52.775
Come on. Don't want you
to miss the overture.


952
01:09:53.694 --> 01:09:55.528
Think we should get ready, boys?

953
01:09:55.738 --> 01:09:58.906
No, we can finish this hand.
Nobody's made a pep talk yet.


954
01:09:59.366 --> 01:10:00.450
Pep talk?

955
01:10:01.035 --> 01:10:03.828
Yeah. I never seen an opening night yet
without some guy...


956
01:10:04.038 --> 01:10:07.623
...gets all the poor actors together
and makes them a long speech:


957
01:10:07.833 --> 01:10:09.542
"They should be brilliant."

958
01:10:09.877 --> 01:10:12.378
On-stage, please. 
Everybody on-stage.

959
01:10:14.840 --> 01:10:16.716
Mr. Cordova wants to say
a few words.


960
01:10:16.925 --> 01:10:20.261
Come on, girls. Hurry up. Let's go.
Step right along.


961
01:10:26.685 --> 01:10:30.521
Company, a final word.
You've all been just wonderful.


962
01:10:30.731 --> 01:10:32.231
Thanks for your cooperation.

963
01:10:32.441 --> 01:10:35.401
Tonight, we're about to perform
before an audience in a theater.


964
01:10:35.611 --> 01:10:38.321
It's not only a temple of the arts,
but a place of business.


965
01:10:38.530 --> 01:10:41.699
And I feel we have here a venture
that is successful on both counts.


966
01:10:41.909 --> 01:10:45.161
Nothing to be nervous about.
We've got to keep our wits and do a show.


967
01:10:45.371 --> 01:10:47.747
There will be rough spots,
but we'll smooth them out.


968
01:10:47.956 --> 01:10:50.375
Remember, that's what
we came out of town for.


969
01:10:50.584 --> 01:10:53.503
Up to now,
I've been giving you orders as director...


970
01:10:54.088 --> 01:10:57.507
...but when next you see me,
I shall be just as one of you...


971
01:10:57.716 --> 01:11:00.468
...an eager ham, anxious to make good.

972
01:11:01.053 --> 01:11:03.846
Actors, let's go.

973
01:11:04.056 --> 01:11:06.474
All right, people.
Get ready for the tableau, girls.


974
01:11:06.683 --> 01:11:09.268
Finish your make-up.
Come on, girls. Let's go.


975
01:11:10.979 --> 01:11:12.897
I'm so glad you folks could come.

976
01:11:13.107 --> 01:11:16.025
And don't forget the big party
at the hotel after the show.


977
01:11:16.235 --> 01:11:18.444
The whole cast will be there.
You'll meet them all.


978
01:11:18.654 --> 01:11:21.656
Of course, I have to go backstage
to congratulate them afterwards.


979
01:11:23.117 --> 01:11:25.326
I'll see you all at the party.

980
01:11:25.536 --> 01:11:27.328
All New York is here.

981
01:11:28.247 --> 01:11:30.164
Big party at the hotel after the show.

982
01:11:30.374 --> 01:11:33.709
I'll look for you. Big party, big show.
Come on, now.


983
01:11:35.796 --> 01:11:38.714
We don't want to miss a thing.
Now, don't forget the party.


984
01:11:38.924 --> 01:11:42.510
Evelyn, big party at the hotel
after the show.


985
01:11:42.719 --> 01:11:44.303
I'll look for you.

986
01:11:45.764 --> 01:11:47.432
Champagne's on me.

987
01:12:33.479 --> 01:12:36.647
Shall I drive you to the hotel, sir,
to the party?


988
01:12:38.108 --> 01:12:39.317
No. Drive me to the station.

989
01:12:39.526 --> 01:12:42.320
Maybe I can still make the 11:40
back to New York.


990
01:12:42.529 --> 01:12:43.738
Yes, sir.

991
01:13:16.021 --> 01:13:19.565
- Good evening.
- I was looking for The Band Wagon party.


992
01:13:19.775 --> 01:13:21.317
This is it, sir.

993
01:13:39.795 --> 01:13:41.796
This way, please.

994
01:14:14.288 --> 01:14:17.081
- Are you leaving, sir?
- Yes. Good night.


995
01:14:18.917 --> 01:14:21.043
We must do this more often.

996
01:14:25.424 --> 01:14:30.636
Oh, give me something
To remember you by


997
01:14:32.598 --> 01:14:37.101
When you are far away from me

998
01:14:39.938 --> 01:14:41.897
Some little something

999
01:14:42.107 --> 01:14:43.941
It's all Annie's fault.

1000
01:14:45.110 --> 01:14:47.945
I should have listened to my mother.
She told me only to be in hit shows.


1001
01:14:51.992 --> 01:14:53.534
Hi, I don't want to barge in.

1002
01:14:53.744 --> 01:14:56.203
I just want to tell you all
how great I think you are.


1003
01:14:56.413 --> 01:14:58.247
I didn't get a chance
to know you very well.


1004
01:14:58.457 --> 01:15:03.252
- I'm sorry I messed up the show for you.
- Wait a minute, come on in, have a drink.


1005
01:15:03.462 --> 01:15:06.505
- I don't want to crash the party.
- Give Mr. Hunter a drink.


1006
01:15:06.715 --> 01:15:09.300
- What do you say, Scotch, rye, or beer?
- Beer's fine.


1007
01:15:09.509 --> 01:15:12.178
- One beer, coming up.
- Want some pizza pie?


1008
01:15:12.387 --> 01:15:15.264
How about a sandwich?
We've got ham and deviled egg.


1009
01:15:15.474 --> 01:15:17.391
I've had enough of both for one night.

1010
01:15:23.357 --> 01:15:27.652
Far away
Me, oh, my


1011
01:15:27.861 --> 01:15:31.572
Only yesterday

1012
01:15:35.535 --> 01:15:38.412
There we were, the whole act,
the 10 Tapping Troubadours.


1013
01:15:38.622 --> 01:15:40.581
The 10 Tapping Troubadours?

1014
01:15:40.791 --> 01:15:42.083
Yeah, believe it or not...

1015
01:15:42.292 --> 01:15:44.585
...we were stranded in Pittsburgh
with $3 between us...


1016
01:15:44.795 --> 01:15:47.755
...crammed into one room
the size of that closet.


1017
01:15:49.049 --> 01:15:52.134
Gaby, come on in.
We're having a good old-fashioned wake.


1018
01:15:53.387 --> 01:15:55.054
I've been looking all over for you.

1019
01:15:55.263 --> 01:15:56.305
Where is Paul?

1020
01:15:56.515 --> 01:15:59.350
He's at a very exclusive wake
with Jeff and the Martons.


1021
01:15:59.559 --> 01:16:01.727
Can I get you a drink, Gaby?
How about a beer?


1022
01:16:01.937 --> 01:16:03.771
How about some popcorn?

1023
01:16:03.980 --> 01:16:05.398
Tony!

1024
01:16:06.858 --> 01:16:08.859
Lily, Lester, come on in.

1025
01:16:09.695 --> 01:16:12.947
Are you sure? Don't you remember?
We wrote that thing.


1026
01:16:13.156 --> 01:16:15.741
This is a wonderful party. Come on in.

1027
01:16:16.368 --> 01:16:19.620
Who's going to go out and get the beer?
Okay, Sis, you're elected.


1028
01:16:19.830 --> 01:16:21.706
Tony, watch this!

1029
01:16:24.418 --> 01:16:25.793
More beer!

1030
01:16:26.920 --> 01:16:29.255
I'll never forget.
You blew a gasket.


1031
01:16:29.464 --> 01:16:31.632
You were really gone. Come on.

1032
01:16:34.720 --> 01:16:36.554
Come on, Tony. 
Come on, get with it.

1033
01:16:37.973 --> 01:16:40.141
How I love the glass of beer

1034
01:16:40.350 --> 01:16:41.976
More beer

1035
01:16:42.561 --> 01:16:47.189
- Beer goes very good with beer
- More beer


1036
01:16:47.399 --> 01:16:52.027
When I'm drinking beer I'm thinking
"Ach, life is dear"


1037
01:16:52.237 --> 01:16:57.074
But there's someone I love
Even more than beer


1038
01:16:58.827 --> 01:17:03.289
I love Louisa
Louisa loves me


1039
01:17:03.707 --> 01:17:08.169
When we rode on the merry-go-round
I kissed Louisa


1040
01:17:08.378 --> 01:17:12.423
And then Louisa
Louisa kissed me


1041
01:17:12.966 --> 01:17:17.428
We were so happy
So happy and free


1042
01:17:17.721 --> 01:17:21.891
Ach! Ach! But she's a
Beautiful Louisa


1043
01:17:22.058 --> 01:17:24.018
Ach! When I choose 'em

1044
01:17:24.227 --> 01:17:26.645
I never want to lose 'em

1045
01:17:26.855 --> 01:17:31.317
Someday Louisa
Louisa will be


1046
01:17:31.526 --> 01:17:34.487
More als just a Fräulein to me

1047
01:17:38.325 --> 01:17:42.536
- Frenchmen love a glass of wine
- More beer


1048
01:17:42.746 --> 01:17:47.166
- The English think the whiskey's fine
- More beer


1049
01:17:47.375 --> 01:17:51.754
But when I comb off all the foam off
I drink a toast


1050
01:17:51.963 --> 01:17:54.673
To the Germans and the Mädchen

1051
01:17:54.883 --> 01:17:58.344
I love most

1052
01:18:16.947 --> 01:18:21.367
Ach! Ach! But she's a
Beautiful Louisa


1053
01:18:21.576 --> 01:18:26.205
Ach! When I choose 'em
I never want to lose 'em


1054
01:18:43.849 --> 01:18:48.143
Ach! Ach! But she's a
Beautiful Louisa


1055
01:18:48.353 --> 01:18:52.523
Ach! When I choose 'em
I never want to lose 'em


1056
01:18:52.732 --> 01:18:56.944
Someday Louisa
Louisa will be


1057
01:18:57.153 --> 01:19:00.239
More than just a Fräulein to me

1058
01:19:00.448 --> 01:19:04.660
More beer!
More beer!


1059
01:19:04.870 --> 01:19:08.539
More beer!

1060
01:19:24.222 --> 01:19:27.808
Gosh, with all this raw talent around,
why can't us kids get together...


1061
01:19:28.018 --> 01:19:29.351
...and put on ourselves a show?

1062
01:19:29.561 --> 01:19:33.314
Maybe we can find ourselves
a barn or something, and maybe...


1063
01:19:36.902 --> 01:19:39.403
I could stand anything but failure.

1064
01:19:40.822 --> 01:19:43.240
- Where's the telephone?
- In there.


1065
01:19:50.749 --> 01:19:53.292
Give me Jeff Cordova's room, please.

1066
01:19:54.461 --> 01:19:57.922
Hello, Jeff. This is Tony.
Now, don't say anything. Just listen.


1067
01:19:58.131 --> 01:20:00.674
I'm here with all the kids,
and we've come to a decision.


1068
01:20:00.884 --> 01:20:04.678
We're not closing this show,
if you can call it a show. We're going on.


1069
01:20:04.888 --> 01:20:08.182
We're going to keep it on the road
and redo it from top to bottom.


1070
01:20:08.391 --> 01:20:10.184
It won't be a modern version of Faust...

1071
01:20:10.393 --> 01:20:12.937
...Pilgrim's Progress, or the Book of Job
in swing time.


1072
01:20:13.146 --> 01:20:15.773
It'll be our show,
the show we started out to do...


1073
01:20:15.982 --> 01:20:18.525
...the book the Martons wrote,
with the songs you threw out.


1074
01:20:18.735 --> 01:20:21.570
It'll have laughs and entertainment.
You remember entertainment?


1075
01:20:21.780 --> 01:20:23.697
Look, we'd love to
have you with us, Jeff.

1076
01:20:23.907 --> 01:20:25.950
But if you're not,
it won't make any difference.


1077
01:20:26.159 --> 01:20:27.534
We're going ahead just the same.

1078
01:20:27.744 --> 01:20:30.579
We're going to put this thing across,
aren't we, kids?


1079
01:20:30.789 --> 01:20:32.164
All right. What do you say?

1080
01:20:32.374 --> 01:20:33.958
Hello? Nobody here.

1081
01:20:34.167 --> 01:20:37.127
This is the chambermaid, but if you want...

1082
01:20:37.337 --> 01:20:40.422
...I'll leave a message for Mr. Cordova.
- Thank you, madam.


1083
01:20:40.966 --> 01:20:42.383
He isn't in.

1084
01:20:53.895 --> 01:20:56.313
Jeff, did you hear what I said?

1085
01:20:57.983 --> 01:21:01.318
Tony, I've learned one thing in the theater,
and it's this:


1086
01:21:01.528 --> 01:21:04.780
one man has to be at the helm,
the rest take orders.


1087
01:21:05.657 --> 01:21:09.410
I believe in what you said.
I got carried away in the wrong direction.


1088
01:21:09.619 --> 01:21:14.331
You've got to be the boss, Tony.
I think you can pull this off brilliantly...


1089
01:21:15.583 --> 01:21:17.918
...and I'd like to
be a part of it.

1090
01:21:20.005 --> 01:21:21.088
Jeff, you're all right.

1091
01:21:21.297 --> 01:21:23.424
I must tell you one thing.
There isn't any money.


1092
01:21:23.633 --> 01:21:26.760
Colonel Todd and the backers
have stolen away into the night.


1093
01:21:26.970 --> 01:21:28.012
- We've got backers.
- Who?


1094
01:21:28.221 --> 01:21:30.305
A bunch of painters.
A fellow named Degas from...


1095
01:21:30.515 --> 01:21:33.434
- You wouldn't sell your paintings.
- Sure, they love the theater.


1096
01:21:33.643 --> 01:21:37.604
I figure we need five or six weeks on tour
to do what we have to do with this show.


1097
01:21:37.814 --> 01:21:40.232
- Jeff, would you help us with bookings?
- Of course.


1098
01:21:40.442 --> 01:21:43.736
Hal, have you got paper and pencil?
We can send a telegram.


1099
01:21:46.114 --> 01:21:48.198
- Washington? Washington's open.
- And Boston.


1100
01:21:48.408 --> 01:21:49.450
Boston's very good.

1101
01:21:49.659 --> 01:21:52.828
Can we go to Philadelphia, Detroit,
then come on back to New York?


1102
01:21:53.038 --> 01:21:56.665
- Paul, aren't you excited?
- Yeah. It's wonderful.


1103
01:21:57.709 --> 01:21:59.710
I wish them a lot of luck.

1104
01:22:01.212 --> 01:22:04.548
- This kind of leaves us out.
- Why?


1105
01:22:05.008 --> 01:22:08.177
With Tony doing the dances,
it's not going to be my kind of show.


1106
01:22:08.386 --> 01:22:11.138
Yours, either. 
I don't want you to do it.

1107
01:22:12.891 --> 01:22:15.142
I wouldn't think of leaving the show, Paul.

1108
01:22:15.351 --> 01:22:20.064
- I've worked too hard on your career to...
- It's my career, and I want to stay.


1109
01:22:21.775 --> 01:22:24.902
I'm taking the 9:00 train
tomorrow morning for New York.


1110
01:22:25.111 --> 01:22:27.071
I expect you to be there.

1111
01:22:28.823 --> 01:22:30.741
Have a nice trip, Paul.

1112
01:22:36.039 --> 01:22:38.665
Dancers, singers, the sketches.

1113
01:22:42.712 --> 01:22:46.006
Listen, kids,
it's going to mean rehearsing every day...


1114
01:22:46.424 --> 01:22:48.509
...all day, right up to curtain time.

1115
01:22:48.718 --> 01:22:51.970
We're going to put in new numbers,
and learn them as fast as we can...


1116
01:22:52.180 --> 01:22:54.973
...and we're going to
yank out all that junk.

1117
01:22:56.434 --> 01:22:59.812
We've got our schedule all worked out,
and it looks pretty good now.


1118
01:23:00.021 --> 01:23:03.023
Philadelphia, Boston, Pittsburgh...

1119
01:23:03.233 --> 01:23:05.526
...Washington, Baltimore...

1120
01:23:21.417 --> 01:23:26.296
I see a new sun
up in a new sky

1121
01:23:26.506 --> 01:23:31.135
And my whole horizon
Has reached a new high


1122
01:23:31.761 --> 01:23:36.348
Yesterday my heart sang a blue song

1123
01:23:36.558 --> 01:23:41.353
But today hear it
hum a cheery new song

1124
01:23:41.563 --> 01:23:46.275
I dreamed a new dream
I saw a new face


1125
01:23:46.484 --> 01:23:51.363
And I'm spreading sunshine
All over the place


1126
01:23:51.573 --> 01:23:56.451
With a new point of view
Here's what greets my eye


1127
01:23:57.203 --> 01:23:59.329
- New love
- New love


1128
01:23:59.539 --> 01:24:01.540
- New luck
- New luck


1129
01:24:01.749 --> 01:24:06.420
- New sun
- And there's a new sun


1130
01:24:06.629 --> 01:24:11.550
In the sky

1131
01:24:21.019 --> 01:24:24.938
I guess I'll have to change my plan

1132
01:24:25.982 --> 01:24:30.110
I should've realized
There'd be another man


1133
01:24:30.653 --> 01:24:34.990
I overlooked that point completely

1134
01:24:35.491 --> 01:24:39.745
Until the big affair began

